<subSubSection lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="24" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="22.[151,1437,1806,2014]" lastBlockId="23.[151,1437,152,323]" lastPageId="23" lastPageNumber="24" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,617,1806,1833]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Description of Brazilian specimens.</emphasis>
Corallum sympodial irregularly branched, without pinnules, with branches in more than one plane (
<figureCitation box="[452,549,1843,1869]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1700,1725]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,481,1681]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[151,1436,481,1681]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 10. MNRJ 6585: Leiopathes glaberrima (Esper, 1792), collected in Brazil. a—Corallum morphology; b—Terminal branchlets; c—Organization of spines; d—Spines magnified." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3528964" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3528964/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 10a</figureCitation>
). Corallum usually branched up to the 8th order (
<figureCitation box="[1099,1195,1843,1869]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="23.[151,250,1862,1887]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,337,1842]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1436,337,1842]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 11. MNRJ 8599: Leiopathes glaberrima (Esper, 1792) collected in the Rio Grande Rise. a—Corallum morphology; b—Terminal branchlets; c—Organization of spines; d—Spines magnified." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3528966" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3528966/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 11a</figureCitation>
). Terminal branchlets arising irregularly on lower order branches (
<figureCitation box="[663,763,1879,1906]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1700,1725]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,481,1681]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[151,1436,481,1681]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 10. MNRJ 6585: Leiopathes glaberrima (Esper, 1792), collected in Brazil. a—Corallum morphology; b—Terminal branchlets; c—Organization of spines; d—Spines magnified." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3528964" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3528964/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 10b</figureCitation>
). Terminal branchlets measuring between 3 and 
<quantity box="[1323,1405,1879,1906]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="40.0">40 mm</quantity>
in length, more common 
<quantity box="[401,507,1915,1942]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.85" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="0.7" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="18.5" valueMax="30.0" valueMin="7.0">7–30 mm</quantity>
(
<figureCitation box="[521,616,1915,1942]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="23.[151,250,1862,1887]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,337,1842]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1436,337,1842]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 11. MNRJ 8599: Leiopathes glaberrima (Esper, 1792) collected in the Rio Grande Rise. a—Corallum morphology; b—Terminal branchlets; c—Organization of spines; d—Spines magnified." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3528966" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3528966/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">Fig. 11b</figureCitation>
). Diameter of terminal branchlets near the base between 0.19 and 
<quantity box="[1345,1432,1914,1942]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.5 mm</quantity>
, usually close to 
<quantity box="[333,423,1951,1978]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="0.3">0.3 mm</quantity>
. Diameter of tips of terminal branchlets approximately 
<quantity box="[1046,1134,1951,1978]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="0.1">0.1 mm</quantity>
, ranging between 0.05 and 
<quantity box="[151,255,1987,2014]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.9" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" unit="mm" value="0.19">0.19 mm</quantity>
. Corallum brownish. Angle of insertion of branches between 30° and 70°, being more common between 40° and 60°. Distance between adjacent branchlets 
<quantity box="[727,822,152,179]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" unit="mm" value="3.5" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="2.0">2–5 mm</quantity>
, ranging from 
<quantity box="[988,1105,153,179]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="3.0" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" unit="mm" value="5.5" valueMax="8.0" valueMin="3.0">3 to 8 mm</quantity>
, with 3–5 branchlets per centimeter. Spines arranged in up to 6 rows (in lateral view), but usually 3–4, absent on larger branches and stem, with tips round and smooth (
<figureCitation box="[421,501,225,251]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="22.[151,250,1700,1725]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,481,1681]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[151,1436,481,1681]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURE 10. MNRJ 6585: Leiopathes glaberrima (Esper, 1792), collected in Brazil. a—Corallum morphology; b—Terminal branchlets; c—Organization of spines; d—Spines magnified." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3528964" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3528964/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
c–d; 
<figureCitation box="[559,637,225,252]" captionStart="FIGURE 11" captionStartId="23.[151,250,1862,1887]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,337,1842]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[151,1436,337,1842]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURE 11. MNRJ 8599: Leiopathes glaberrima (Esper, 1792) collected in the Rio Grande Rise. a—Corallum morphology; b—Terminal branchlets; c—Organization of spines; d—Spines magnified." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3528966" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3528966/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
c–d). Spines 
<quantity box="[786,950,225,251]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" metricValueMax="7" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" unit="mm" value="0.045" valueMax="0.07" valueMin="0.02">0.02–0.07 mm</quantity>
high, being more common 
<quantity box="[1265,1433,224,251]" metricMagnitude="-5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.5" metricValueMax="5.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" unit="mm" value="0.035" valueMax="0.05" valueMin="0.02">0.02–0.05 mm</quantity>
. Width of base of spines varying between 0.036 and 0.100 mm. Spines in a same row 
<quantity box="[1100,1263,260,287]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.2" metricValueMax="9.5" metricValueMin="0.8999999999999999" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" unit="mm" value="0.52" valueMax="0.95" valueMin="0.09">0.09–0.95 mm</quantity>
apart, in densities of 2–5 spines per millimeter. Polyps 
<quantity box="[608,743,297,323]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5999999999999999" metricValueMax="2.3" metricValueMin="0.9" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" unit="mm" value="1.5999999999999999" valueMax="2.3" valueMin="0.9">0.9–2.3 mm</quantity>
in diameter, with density of 4–6 polyps per centimeter.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3528966" ID-Zenodo-Dep="3528966" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3528966/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" startId="23.[151,250,1862,1887]" targetBox="[151,1436,337,1842]" targetPageId="23">
